184.title: List of Carmina Burana
table: A meditation on true nobility, defined not by lineage but by virtue and moral integrity, contrasting it with degenerate aristocracy.
The poem denounces the corruption of the clergy, criticizing priests and levites who sell spiritual goods and abandon moral conduct.
Explores hatred and rivalry, suggesting that hatred harms the hater more than the hated, leading only to suffering and disillusionment.
Envy is portrayed as a destructive passion that consumes the soul, harming both the envious individual and their target.
Fortune is depicted as fickle and unpredictable, emphasizing the instability of human life and the futility of worldly ambition.
External circumstances may change, but a steadfast soul remains unchanged; true strength lies in moral perseverance.
A lament over Fortune’s volatility, which raises and destroys human lives without warning.
Expresses human helplessness before the cruel and cyclical power of Fortune, to which all are subject.
Fortune is described as capricious, elevating the lowly and destroying the powerful, emphasizing social volatility.
Regnabo; regno; regnavi; sum sine regno
Reflects on the fleeting nature of political power and social ascent, emphasizing their ultimate emptiness.
Contrasts virtue and vice, condemns avarice, and promotes generosity as a moral ideal.
Advocates moral moderation, asserting that virtue lies between extremes and excess leads to ruin.
Celebrates divine truth as the supreme guide against sin and deception, emphasizing salvation through faith.
An exhortation to moral renewal and faith, stressing that salvation depends on virtuous living.
Stresses the importance of moral and spiritual education and living according to one’s teachings.
Criticizes worldly falsehoods and urges the pursuit of eternal spiritual values.
Reflects on living according to moral law and warns against a life without purpose or direction.
Faith, Trust in God, Last Judgment
Denounces the corruption of religious institutions. Once devoted to prayer, monastic life has fallen into ambition and internal conflict.
A brief reflection asserting that knowledge without practice is vain and that ignorance leads to spiritual darkness.
A severe critique of medieval society and clerical corruption, portraying moral hypocrisy and institutional decay.
A reminder of human mortality and the futility of earthly possessions; only the soul possesses eternal value.
An exhortation urging priests to purify themselves spiritually before celebrating the Mass.
A series of moral aphorisms emphasizing divine grace as the source of merit and the moral value of moderation and joy.
A fierce satire against hypocrisy and corruption in Rome, where money controls justice and morality.
Laments Rome’s spiritual decay, dominated by simony and avarice, and urges repentance before divine punishment arrives.
Initium sancti evangelii secundum Marcas Argenti
A parody of the Gospel exposing corruption in the Roman Curia, where wealth determines access, healing, and justice.
Biblical and eschatological reflections on faith, idolatry, and conversion, invoking divine protection for those marked by the cross.
A lament for the loss of Jerusalem and desecration of the Holy Sepulchre, calling Christians to defend the faith through crusade.

185.title: List of Carmina Burana
table: Encourages abandoning study for youthful pleasures. Contrasts old age and seriousness with natural youthful instincts for fun and love.
Celebrates the sun’s return and spring. Nature awakens, joy spreads, and the refrain calls for singing and dancing.
A joyful invitation to celebrate love and youth against aging. Refrain encourages exploring love’s pleasures.
An incitement to love and pleasure among young people and virgins, inspired by birdsong. Refrain celebrates vitality and youthful joy.
Depicts Aeneas and Dido in Carthage, their passionate love, and tragic ending with Dido’s suicide. Explores love, passion, fate, and grief.
Briefly recounts Paris, Helen, Aeneas, and Dido, highlighting love’s capacity for joy and suffering.
Paris arms himself with love, abducts Helen, and triggers war.
Aeneas causes Dido’s death; she takes her life with the Trojan hero’s sword.
Dido laments Eneas’ abandonment and Carthage’s doomed fate, expressing suffering, anger, and despair.

186.title: List of Carmina Burana
table: This short carmen states that those with wealth are loved and honored, while the poor are despised and oppressed.
The author seeks to win favor through his writing skills, while also asking for help to alleviate the burden of poverty.
Describes a chess battle, referencing game pieces and conflict between sides.
Nu lebe ich mir alrest werde
Fragment of Walther von der Vogelweide's Palästinalied, expressing joy at seeing the Holy Land.
Provides guidance for a balanced life: rise early, dedicate time to reading, eat and drink moderately, sleep a little, meditate, and write.
Expresses a wish to enjoy the labors of peasants and clerics, their women, and rejoice in their deaths.
States that it is customary to give things for things and words for words.
